WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.780 --> 00:00:04.700
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:19.040 --> 00:00:20.340
&gt;&gt; Michelle Choe: Hi everyone.

00:00:20.340 --> 00:00:22.020
Welcome back.

00:00:22.020 --> 00:00:24.110
So we're going to move
on to the second panel,

00:00:24.110 --> 00:00:26.990
which is on ownership
and contractual issues.

00:00:26.990 --> 00:00:29.650
The goal of this panel
is to explore the state

00:00:29.650 --> 00:00:34.130
of contract law vis-Ã -vis
software-enabled everyday products

00:00:34.130 --> 00:00:38.580 position:56%
and how contracts such as end user
license agreements impact investment

00:00:38.580 --> 00:00:42.090
in and the dissemination and
use of everyday products,

00:00:42.090 --> 00:00:45.800
including whether any
legislative action is necessary.

00:00:45.800 --> 00:00:51.910
So before we start, we should
first introduce the new member

00:00:51.910 --> 00:00:55.190
to our section.

00:00:55.190 --> 00:00:56.490
&gt;&gt; Erik Bertin: Good morning.

00:00:56.490 --> 00:00:57.790
I'm Erik Bertin.

00:00:57.790 --> 00:00:59.090
I'm the Deputy Director

00:00:59.090 --> 00:01:00.390
for Registration here
at the Copyright Office.

00:01:00.390 --> 00:01:03.520
&gt;&gt; Michelle Choe: And we should
also have the new members

00:01:03.520 --> 00:01:07.460
on the panel introduce
themselves and their affiliations.

00:01:07.460 --> 00:01:11.670
So, if we could start
with you, Mr. Perzanowski.

00:01:11.670 --> 00:01:13.260
&gt;&gt; Aaron Perzanowski: My
name is Aaron Perzanowski.

00:01:13.260 --> 00:01:14.560
I'm a Professor of Law

00:01:14.560 --> 00:01:18.890
at Case Western Reserve
University in Cleveland, Ohio.

00:01:18.890 --> 00:01:24.690 position:56%
I've been thinking and writing about
issues concerning consumer ownership

00:01:24.690 --> 00:01:28.420
of digital goods for a long time.

00:01:28.420 --> 00:01:29.870
&gt;&gt; Michelle Choe: And Mr. Harbeson.

00:01:29.870 --> 00:01:34.800
&gt;&gt; Eric Harbeson: I'm Eric Harbeson
from the Music Library Association.

00:01:34.800 --> 00:01:36.100
&gt;&gt; Michelle Choe: OK, great.

00:01:36.100 --> 00:01:37.400
Thank you.

00:01:37.400 --> 00:01:41.740
So, after reading the comments
we've received in this area,

00:01:41.740 --> 00:01:45.610
we've identified two areas
of particular interest.

00:01:45.610 --> 00:01:48.980
First, what are the legal
or practical rationales

00:01:48.980 --> 00:01:52.340
for employing end user license
agreements or other types

00:01:52.340 --> 00:01:56.070
of agreements in the context of
software-enabled consumer products?

00:01:56.070 --> 00:01:59.770
And second, are such agreements
having any practical effect

00:01:59.770 --> 00:02:02.670
in the marketplace in terms
of limiting the availability

00:02:02.670 --> 00:02:05.890
of exceptions and limitations
in the copyright act?

00:02:05.890 --> 00:02:10.830
So, if anyone would like to
start addressing one or both

00:02:10.830 --> 00:02:12.640
of those issues, that'd be great.

00:02:12.640 --> 00:02:14.940
So, Mr. Bergmayer.

00:02:16.640 --> 00:02:17.940
&gt;&gt; John Bergmayer: Yeah.

00:02:17.940 --> 00:02:21.720
So, I think one of the issues
with software, in particular,

00:02:21.720 --> 00:02:26.840
is that where it goes beyond
contract law is that if the seller

00:02:26.840 --> 00:02:29.200
of a software product or a
software-enabled product is

00:02:29.200 --> 00:02:31.210
in some way saying that you never--

00:02:31.210 --> 00:02:34.140
the buyer never actually
owns the copy.

00:02:34.140 --> 00:02:38.110
That doesn't just affect the
relationship between the seller

00:02:38.110 --> 00:02:40.060
and the buyer, it has
downstream effects

00:02:40.060 --> 00:02:44.880
because the first-sale doctrine
then never kicks in and people

00:02:44.880 --> 00:02:48.560
who are not privity to the sales
contract between the seller

00:02:48.560 --> 00:02:51.650
and the buyer would also
be infringing copyright

00:02:51.650 --> 00:02:52.950
for later distributions.

00:02:52.950 --> 00:02:56.120
So I think that is one of the
particularly dangerous areas

00:02:56.120 --> 00:02:58.240
with the notion that a seller

00:02:58.240 --> 00:03:00.890
of a software product
can reserve ownership.

00:03:00.890 --> 00:03:04.010
And also, I think you'll see
in a lot of the comments,

00:03:04.010 --> 00:03:07.820
there was agreement that the
law doesn't need to change

00:03:07.820 --> 00:03:10.720
but different people have different
idea of what the law means.

00:03:10.720 --> 00:03:12.770
When I say the law it
doesn't need to change,

00:03:12.770 --> 00:03:15.460
I think that these parallel
doctrines that have come

00:03:15.460 --> 00:03:20.130 position:56%
up where software vendors uniquely
among all copyright holders have the

00:03:20.130 --> 00:03:22.180
ability to sell you
something and say

00:03:22.180 --> 00:03:25.630 position:56%
that they didn't really sell it you,
that has no basis in the statute.

00:03:25.630 --> 00:03:29.320
It defies common sense and legal
logic and yet we've allowed it

00:03:29.320 --> 00:03:32.510
to grow up in the software
industry to sort

00:03:32.510 --> 00:03:36.020
of arrange its business models
around this legal concept

00:03:36.020 --> 00:03:39.290
where in other areas
plenty of other sellers

00:03:39.290 --> 00:03:42.120
of copyrighted products have
tried to do the exact same thing

00:03:42.120 --> 00:03:45.580 position:56%
and they've been smacked down by the
courts, you know, the foundational

00:03:45.580 --> 00:03:50.490
for sale cases about the
attempt to withhold rights--

00:03:50.490 --> 00:03:56.010 position:56%
resale rights from customers, the
people who have given people sample.

00:03:56.010 --> 00:03:58.390
Music have tried to say,
well, you can't resell this

00:03:58.390 --> 00:03:59.690
because you don't really own it

00:03:59.690 --> 00:04:02.060
and courts have taken the
very common sense view

00:04:02.060 --> 00:04:05.470
that if you're transferring a
physical item to someone for keeps,

00:04:05.470 --> 00:04:08.850
that means they own it and just
sort of boilerplate language

00:04:08.850 --> 00:04:10.970
in a sales agreement
between a seller

00:04:10.970 --> 00:04:14.860
and a buyer can't really change
that basic economic reality.

00:04:14.860 --> 00:04:18.630
And it is this-- you know,
this is the issue that sort

00:04:18.630 --> 00:04:21.570
of got me involved in this area.

00:04:21.570 --> 00:04:24.260 position:56%
You know, I first started looking
about this stuff and the Vernor case

00:04:24.260 --> 00:04:26.200
which I think came
out the wrong way.

00:04:26.200 --> 00:04:30.560 position:56%
And I think if we just revisit
these doctrines which are judge-made

00:04:30.560 --> 00:04:34.360
and have no basis in the statute,
we can undo a lot of the real

00:04:34.360 --> 00:04:35.860
and potential consumer harm.

00:04:35.860 --> 00:04:41.120 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Sy Damle: So, can I-- I mean, so,
you know, when I re-read Vernor--

00:04:41.120 --> 00:04:46.630
I mean, Vernor is based on an
older case from 1977 called Wise

00:04:46.630 --> 00:04:48.300
which didn't involve up a software.

00:04:48.300 --> 00:04:50.670 position:56%
It involved a motion picture prints.

00:04:50.670 --> 00:04:54.280
And with the court basically said
there was-- I mean it reached--

00:04:54.280 --> 00:04:58.010
it sort of reversed the
convictions I think in that case

00:04:58.010 --> 00:05:01.370
on other grounds but it
did say that, you know,

00:05:01.370 --> 00:05:05.490
the court discussed a sort of
VIP prints of motion pictures

00:05:05.490 --> 00:05:07.950
like staying [inaudible]
and said that,

00:05:07.950 --> 00:05:09.800
you know, those could be licensed.

00:05:09.800 --> 00:05:13.300
And so I'm just wondering
what you say about--

00:05:13.300 --> 00:05:15.960
I mean, just to your point that
this is something that's unique

00:05:15.960 --> 00:05:18.480
to software, I'm just wondering
whether you could address sort

00:05:18.480 --> 00:05:20.600
of why and it's a reasoning.

00:05:20.600 --> 00:05:23.640
&gt;&gt; John Bergmayer: There absolutely
can be situations where I sort

00:05:23.640 --> 00:05:28.980
of transfer physical custody
of a physical item to a buyer

00:05:28.980 --> 00:05:31.990 position:56%
or another person where they don't
really own it but I think there have

00:05:31.990 --> 00:05:35.290
to be facts to support that,
it can't just be routine

00:05:35.290 --> 00:05:37.780
like I just sort of add it to
every single thing that I sell,

00:05:37.780 --> 00:05:42.190 position:56%
there has to be some sort verifiable
requirement that they destroyed

00:05:42.190 --> 00:05:44.250
after use or that they return it,

00:05:44.250 --> 00:05:46.790
or there has to be some
sort of reality to that.

00:05:46.790 --> 00:05:48.090
It can't just be something

00:05:48.090 --> 00:05:51.850
that anytime anyone buys a consumer
product, the example that I pulled

00:05:51.850 --> 00:05:54.790
out was-- in our comments
but I could have found it

00:05:54.790 --> 00:06:00.520
in probably any product is
the Nest thermostat license

00:06:00.520 --> 00:06:03.850
which simultaneously says that you,
the buyer, don't really own this,

00:06:03.850 --> 00:06:06.480
you don't own the copy of
the software which, you know,

00:06:06.480 --> 00:06:10.140
is a physical thing because
copies are always material objects

00:06:10.140 --> 00:06:11.970
but it also describes
you as the buyer.

00:06:11.970 --> 00:06:15.440 position:56%
And it's just contradictory and it's
just put there as a matter of course

00:06:15.440 --> 00:06:17.790
in all software that
is sold to consumers.

00:06:17.790 --> 00:06:19.240
And I think that's the problem,

00:06:19.240 --> 00:06:22.760 position:56%
not that there might be exceptional
circumstances where, yeah, you know,

00:06:22.760 --> 00:06:25.520
if you're giving it back or if
you're really just renting it

00:06:25.520 --> 00:06:28.300
or it's in a unique market that
has particular characteristics

00:06:28.300 --> 00:06:29.780
like film prints.

00:06:29.780 --> 00:06:33.310
But I think it is the
universalization of this,

00:06:33.310 --> 00:06:35.970
what should be an exceptional
circumstance, that's the problem.

00:06:35.970 --> 00:06:40.040
&gt;&gt; Sy Damle: So, just a couple
of points I'm just curious about.

00:06:40.040 --> 00:06:44.760 position:56%
So-- I mean in Vernor there was--
as a recall, there was a requirement

00:06:44.760 --> 00:06:47.300
that purchaser destroy
the copies when they--

00:06:47.300 --> 00:06:50.190
the original copies when
they purchased the upgrades.

00:06:50.190 --> 00:06:54.300 position:56%
So there was-- the court did mention
that sort of restriction which seems

00:06:54.300 --> 00:06:55.600
to me similar to what was--

00:06:55.600 --> 00:06:56.900
&gt;&gt; John Bergmayer: Yeah.

00:06:56.900 --> 00:06:58.380
But at the same time you can't
just say that you're required

00:06:58.380 --> 00:06:59.770
but there's no actual enforcement.

00:06:59.770 --> 00:07:01.990
I mean, as far as I
know, if you just say

00:07:01.990 --> 00:07:05.880
that just adding a requirement of
distraction to a contract is enough

00:07:05.880 --> 00:07:08.750
to get you into that special
circumstance, then people just

00:07:08.750 --> 00:07:11.220
that every time and it
won't really be enforced.

00:07:11.220 --> 00:07:14.750
I think the point is that there
has to be an economic reality

00:07:14.750 --> 00:07:21.700
that controls whether or not a sale
has taken place, not merely words.

00:07:21.700 --> 00:07:24.060
&gt;&gt; Sy Damle: So, just
a follow-up question.

00:07:24.060 --> 00:07:29.380 position:56%
So I wonder if you could-- So what
the software folk say is that, well,

00:07:29.380 --> 00:07:33.250
if we can't license it, then
things like academic versions

00:07:33.250 --> 00:07:39.220
of software become unviable
where, you know, you sell someone,

00:07:39.220 --> 00:07:43.690
you know, $149 copy of Microsoft
Word with the understanding

00:07:43.690 --> 00:07:45.490
that they're not going to use
it for commercial purposes

00:07:45.490 --> 00:07:49.390
if you don't have some sort of
license that enforces that, right.

00:07:49.390 --> 00:07:50.690
&gt;&gt; John Bergmayer: So two things.

00:07:50.690 --> 00:07:52.720
You can still have a contract,
just the contract only applies

00:07:52.720 --> 00:07:55.020
to the person who ended--
who entered into the contract

00:07:55.020 --> 00:07:57.170
and it doesn't apply to all
potential downstream users.

00:07:57.170 --> 00:08:00.630
So if you do sell something to
someone at a discount and then just

00:08:00.630 --> 00:08:03.430 position:56%
up and reselling it into the general
market, you can use contract law

00:08:03.430 --> 00:08:05.650
to go after them but I think
it would be inappropriate

00:08:05.650 --> 00:08:09.930 position:56%
to go five owners down the line and
start using copyright against people

00:08:09.930 --> 00:08:13.290
who have no idea, never
entered into that contract.

00:08:13.290 --> 00:08:16.550
And second, you know, yes, there
are certain business models

00:08:16.550 --> 00:08:20.000
that might be easier for sellers
if they have certain legal rights

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:21.960
but that doesn't-- that's
not a slam dunk argument

00:08:21.960 --> 00:08:25.110
that those rights should exist and
in fact in other areas like books

00:08:25.110 --> 00:08:29.380
and textbooks we do have special
academic editions or pricing

00:08:29.380 --> 00:08:31.560
and it seems to work just fine.

00:08:31.560 --> 00:08:35.550
There is no concept that
when you buy a textbook,

00:08:35.550 --> 00:08:36.850
you don't really own it.

00:08:36.850 --> 00:08:38.630
And in fact, you know,
I think anyone who used

00:08:38.630 --> 00:08:41.840
to be a student thinks it's great
that you can buy a used textbook

00:08:41.840 --> 00:08:43.850
or sell your textbook
when you're done with it.

00:08:43.850 --> 00:08:48.170
And I just don't see why we need
special software-specific doctrines

00:08:48.170 --> 00:08:51.670
except when they are
specifically codified by statute,

00:08:51.670 --> 00:08:54.120
where there's notion that you
don't own a thing that you bought,

00:08:54.120 --> 00:08:55.470
does not come from the statute.

00:08:55.470 --> 00:08:58.980
That is entirely a
judge-made doctrine.

00:08:58.980 --> 00:09:08.160
&gt;&gt; Michelle Choe: Why don't
we move on to Mr. Band?

00:09:08.160 --> 00:09:09.520
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Band: Thank you.

00:09:09.520 --> 00:09:12.240
So for ORI where this--

00:09:12.240 --> 00:09:13.730
the relationship of contract

00:09:13.730 --> 00:09:19.450
to those issues most obvious
is the first-sale doctrine

00:09:19.450 --> 00:09:21.850
which applies to owners of copies.

00:09:21.850 --> 00:09:26.110
And so if you have software
embedded in a device

00:09:26.110 --> 00:09:29.970
and the software is just
licensed but not sold,

00:09:29.970 --> 00:09:34.320
then the first-sale doctrine
arguably does not apply

00:09:34.320 --> 00:09:40.260
to that piece of software and so
you can't transfer the software

00:09:40.260 --> 00:09:41.980
when you're transferring
the rest of the good.

00:09:41.980 --> 00:09:44.830
And so that makes it
difficult to sell--

00:09:44.830 --> 00:09:48.550
to sell the product in
the secondary market.

00:09:48.550 --> 00:09:53.520
And so that's, you know,
really where we see that issue.

00:09:53.520 --> 00:09:56.920
And as John said, really
the economic realities

00:09:56.920 --> 00:10:02.060
of the transaction are that
when you buy the device,

00:10:02.060 --> 00:10:04.200
you're buying the copy
of the software,

00:10:04.200 --> 00:10:05.500
you're not expected to return it.

00:10:05.500 --> 00:10:12.910
And it seems that obviously
that, you know, if you're able

00:10:12.910 --> 00:10:19.570
to keep the device for its useful
life, let's say if it's 10 years

00:10:19.570 --> 00:10:23.370 position:56%
but let's say-- you know, then if
you want to after five years sell it

00:10:23.370 --> 00:10:25.590
to someone else who could
benefit from the other five years,

00:10:25.590 --> 00:10:28.110
you should be able to do so.

00:10:28.110 --> 00:10:33.180
And so-- But when you
have a contract--

00:10:33.180 --> 00:10:34.760
when you have this
contractual restriction,

00:10:34.760 --> 00:10:36.590
not only do you have
problem that it--

00:10:36.590 --> 00:10:40.280
that could be breaching a contract
but on top of that you're not able

00:10:40.280 --> 00:10:42.210
to take advantage of
the first-sale doctrine.

00:10:42.210 --> 00:10:46.880
So, figuring out the
license piece is--

00:10:46.880 --> 00:10:49.320
or this contractual
piece is critical

00:10:49.320 --> 00:10:56.890
to allowing the alienability of
this piece of personal property.

00:10:56.890 --> 00:11:00.920
And then just-- secondarily,
you know,

00:11:00.920 --> 00:11:03.720
we had talked in the last
session and a lot of people talked

00:11:03.720 --> 00:11:07.090
about reverse engineering
and interoperability and how

00:11:07.090 --> 00:11:11.570
that isn't-- have the
copyright law so clear on that

00:11:11.570 --> 00:11:14.850
and we'll talk a little bit more
about that in the next session.

00:11:14.850 --> 00:11:19.380
But I just wanted to point
out that almost every piece

00:11:19.380 --> 00:11:22.490
of software that's
distributed whether just

00:11:22.490 --> 00:11:25.700
as on the standalone basis
or if it's in a device,

00:11:25.700 --> 00:11:29.650
the license agreement almost
always contains a prohibition

00:11:29.650 --> 00:11:32.360
on reverse engineering
for any purpose.

00:11:32.360 --> 00:11:36.490
So, you know, it's all well and
good that the jurisprudence says

00:11:36.490 --> 00:11:40.210
that it might not be a
copyright infringement

00:11:40.210 --> 00:11:46.320 position:56%
but if you have these pervasive
license agreements that prohibit you

00:11:46.320 --> 00:11:51.190
from engaging in that activity,
obviously there's a tension.

00:11:51.190 --> 00:11:55.760
Now, the question is, getting
to second question, you know,

00:11:55.760 --> 00:11:58.400
what has been the real
impact on that?

00:11:58.400 --> 00:12:03.300 position:56%
Now with respect to these
restrictions on reverse engineering,

00:12:03.300 --> 00:12:05.960
the license restrictions, you
know, there has been litigations,

00:12:05.960 --> 00:12:07.820
the Bowers v. state case.

00:12:07.820 --> 00:12:10.460
And one of the issue there was--

00:12:10.460 --> 00:12:13.670
is the license prohibition

00:12:13.670 --> 00:12:17.390
on reverse engineering is preempted
and, you know, the truth is that--

00:12:17.390 --> 00:12:21.190
you know, in that case, two
judges say not preempted,

00:12:21.190 --> 00:12:23.400
one judge said yes it is preempted.

00:12:23.400 --> 00:12:27.690
I think that that's one of
those really complicated areas

00:12:27.690 --> 00:12:32.310
that I would hope the
study would start delving

00:12:32.310 --> 00:12:37.510
into about this relationship of
when our contract term is preempted

00:12:37.510 --> 00:12:42.370
by the copyright act
and starting to think

00:12:42.370 --> 00:12:45.440
about that and look at that more.

00:12:45.440 --> 00:12:48.710
But I think that that is
an issue that, you know,

00:12:48.710 --> 00:12:51.190
when you counsel clients, you
have talk about and you say, well,

00:12:51.190 --> 00:12:53.820
there's this argument,
there's that argument and,

00:12:53.820 --> 00:12:55.300
you know, do what you need to do.

00:12:55.300 --> 00:12:57.340
And I have a feeling a lot of--

00:12:57.340 --> 00:13:00.070
you know, there are some people who
do go ahead and reverse engineer

00:13:00.070 --> 00:13:05.260
and sort of hope that it's in the
event that there's a litigation

00:13:05.260 --> 00:13:06.710
that will be found to be preempted.

00:13:06.710 --> 00:13:12.250
And I imagined there are other
people who are more risk averse

00:13:12.250 --> 00:13:15.470
and are not reverse engineering

00:13:15.470 --> 00:13:17.750
because they don't
want to take that risk.

00:13:17.750 --> 00:13:19.050
&gt;&gt; Sy Damle: Sorry.

00:13:19.050 --> 00:13:20.970
Is it your understanding that a
violation of such a contract term

00:13:20.970 --> 00:13:27.470 position:56%
against reverse engineering would be
just a breach of contract or would

00:13:27.470 --> 00:13:31.110
that be-- is that somehow tied
to copyright infringement?

00:13:31.110 --> 00:13:32.800
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Band: Well, I think
there's case law that would suggest

00:13:32.800 --> 00:13:35.080
that it could be both,
meaning if it seemed to be--

00:13:35.080 --> 00:13:38.210
if it's a valid restriction
in your--

00:13:38.210 --> 00:13:41.220
you know, I think there is a
case law that would suggest

00:13:41.220 --> 00:13:43.920
that it would be not only
both breach of contract

00:13:43.920 --> 00:13:47.420
and a copyright violation--
copyright infringement.

00:13:47.420 --> 00:13:48.720
