00:42:24.510 --> 00:42:27.420
of publicly provided
versions of software devices

00:42:27.420 --> 00:42:31.140
and they suffered a reputational
harm as a result, and had to

00:42:31.140 --> 00:42:33.950
and were only enable to because
of it being a license to bring

00:42:33.950 --> 00:42:35.470
that back in house and make sure

00:42:35.470 --> 00:42:39.160
that only their software was
associated with those devices,

00:42:39.160 --> 00:42:40.480
we saw that they could recuperate

00:42:40.480 --> 00:42:42.300
from that reputational
harm that they suffered.

00:42:42.300 --> 00:42:44.990
So I think there's a lot
that's unique about software.

00:42:44.990 --> 00:42:49.550
I think as we move forward
into the internet of things

00:42:49.550 --> 00:42:51.580
and embedded software and devices,

00:42:51.580 --> 00:42:54.600
you're going to see more
experimentation in business models,

00:42:54.600 --> 00:42:58.310 position:56%
and some of the legacy practices
will start to fall away because some

00:42:58.310 --> 00:43:01.100
of the legacy dangers will
fall away at the same time.

00:43:01.100 --> 00:43:03.710
But I think all of that is going
to happen much more quickly

00:43:03.710 --> 00:43:05.770
into much more dynamic
fashion than any kind

00:43:05.770 --> 00:43:07.540
of legislative effort would happen.

00:43:07.540 --> 00:43:11.040
So again, as we said
in the last panel,

00:43:11.040 --> 00:43:13.750 position:56%
I think that the existing mechanisms
that are in place both in terms

00:43:13.750 --> 00:43:19.130
of contract law and copyright
exceptions, provide a more fluid

00:43:19.130 --> 00:43:22.440
and a better place to
deal with these issues

00:43:22.440 --> 00:43:24.990
than some kind of legislative
solution.

00:43:24.990 --> 00:43:26.920
&gt;&gt; Michelle Choe: Mr.
Perzanowski, I think you're in

00:43:26.920 --> 00:43:28.360
and we'll go to Mr. Bockert.

00:43:28.360 --> 00:43:31.570
&gt;&gt; Aaron Perzanowski: So there
are a couple of distinctions

00:43:31.570 --> 00:43:35.590
that I think are useful to draw
that I think at some points

00:43:35.590 --> 00:43:37.410
in our discussion have
been confused.

00:43:37.410 --> 00:43:39.450
So first I think we
need to distinguish

00:43:39.450 --> 00:43:43.420
between licensing software and
licensing copies of software.

00:43:43.420 --> 00:43:45.250
And these are two very
different things.

00:43:45.250 --> 00:43:51.300
I also think we have to distinguish
between questions of interpreting

00:43:51.300 --> 00:43:54.900
and enforcing contracts
on the one hand,

00:43:54.900 --> 00:43:58.190 position:56%
and what I think should be the
crucial question for this discussion

00:43:58.190 --> 00:44:02.460
which is how we determine whether a
transfer of ownership has occurred,

00:44:02.460 --> 00:44:07.180
when it comes to particular
copies of software, right.

00:44:07.180 --> 00:44:11.780
And one place I think it make sense
to look is the statute itself.

00:44:11.780 --> 00:44:15.230
You know, unfortunately, for
better or maybe for worse,

00:44:15.230 --> 00:44:19.260
the copyright act does
not define ownership

00:44:19.260 --> 00:44:21.420
in the context of consumers.

00:44:21.420 --> 00:44:26.260
It doesn't define transfers
of ownership.

00:44:26.260 --> 00:44:30.240
But there is language that's useful
in this interpretive question,

00:44:30.240 --> 00:44:34.320
and that language is
in 1063 itself, right?

00:44:34.320 --> 00:44:39.270
1063 defines the kinds
of distributions,

00:44:39.270 --> 00:44:43.680
the copyright law recognizes when
it comes to particular copies,

00:44:43.680 --> 00:44:48.330
and it divides the universe
into two kinds of distributions.

00:44:48.330 --> 00:44:52.730
There are sales and other transfers
of ownership on the one hand,

00:44:52.730 --> 00:44:56.330
and there is rental, lease,
and lending on the other.

00:44:56.330 --> 00:45:00.350
So, every transfer of a copy,
every distribution of a copy,

00:45:00.350 --> 00:45:02.940
is either a transfer of ownership

00:45:02.940 --> 00:45:05.960
or it's a rental, a
lease, or a lending.

00:45:05.960 --> 00:45:08.160
That's really clear
from the statute.

00:45:08.160 --> 00:45:12.800
So the question is if someone wants
to license a copy, which one is it?

00:45:12.800 --> 00:45:16.110
And I think if you look at it

00:45:16.110 --> 00:45:19.790
from that perspective it's actually
a much easier question to answer,

00:45:19.790 --> 00:45:27.020
into the idea of a licensed
copy, is really a myth, right?

00:45:27.020 --> 00:45:28.320
That's not a real thing.

00:45:28.320 --> 00:45:33.190
It's not a transactional form
that the copyright act recognizes.

00:45:33.190 --> 00:45:37.410
You might say that there are
certain kinds of leases or rentals

00:45:37.410 --> 00:45:42.950
or lendings that you want to use
the label license to characterize,

00:45:42.950 --> 00:45:45.480
but there's no such
thing as a licensed copy.

00:45:45.480 --> 00:45:47.310
The software industry has
been pretty successful

00:45:47.310 --> 00:45:49.760
in convincing some courts
that that's a real thing.

00:45:49.760 --> 00:45:51.690
&gt;&gt; Sy Damle: But how
would you-- Sorry.

00:45:51.690 --> 00:45:53.790
How would you explain why is then,

00:45:53.790 --> 00:46:01.120
where they essentially had
perpetual possession of the movie,

00:46:01.120 --> 00:46:04.250
the film prints, but
under restrictions.

00:46:04.250 --> 00:46:05.550
And the courts are--

00:46:05.550 --> 00:46:06.850
&gt;&gt; Aaron Perzanowski:
You're talking about Wise?

00:46:06.850 --> 00:46:08.150
&gt;&gt; Sy Damle: Yeah, Wise.

00:46:08.150 --> 00:46:09.450
&gt;&gt; Aaron Perzanowski: So
we could characterize--

00:46:09.450 --> 00:46:13.180
we could look at the facts of
Wise and say that that is a lease,

00:46:13.180 --> 00:46:16.080
that that is a lending, that there
are certain restrictions, right?

00:46:16.080 --> 00:46:21.150
So, what is it that separates a
transfer of ownership from one

00:46:21.150 --> 00:46:26.960 position:56%
of these other kinds of more
temporary time limited transactions?

00:46:26.960 --> 00:46:29.490
And it might be an
ongoing obligation to pay.

00:46:29.490 --> 00:46:33.100
It might be that there is some
sort of durational limit, right,

00:46:33.100 --> 00:46:36.670
at some point you've got
to give the thing back.

00:46:36.670 --> 00:46:41.190
That fits, I think, reasonably
well into the common understanding

00:46:41.190 --> 00:46:44.730
of leasing or rental, right?

00:46:44.730 --> 00:46:48.890
It's not a transfer of ownership,
if when the thing is given

00:46:48.890 --> 00:46:52.100
to you it is made explicitly clear
that at a certain point you have

00:46:52.100 --> 00:46:54.940
to return the item, you
have to destroy the item,

00:46:54.940 --> 00:46:57.830
that's not a transfer
of ownership, right?

00:46:57.830 --> 00:47:00.740
Ownership entails perpetual
possession,

00:47:00.740 --> 00:47:02.790
no ongoing obligation to pay.

00:47:02.790 --> 00:47:04.510
When those two factors are present,

00:47:04.510 --> 00:47:07.060
what you have is a transfer
of ownership, right?

00:47:07.060 --> 00:47:08.740
&gt;&gt; Sy Damle: So is it your
position that both Vernor

00:47:08.740 --> 00:47:10.040
and Krauss are incorrect?

00:47:10.040 --> 00:47:13.630 position:56%
Not the decision but the reasoning
of both of those cases is incorrect?

00:47:13.630 --> 00:47:16.620
&gt;&gt; Aaron Perzanowski:
I'm happy to say

00:47:16.620 --> 00:47:19.820
that the reasoning in
Vernor is incorrect.

00:47:19.820 --> 00:47:22.840
I think the reasoning
in Krauss is less clear

00:47:22.840 --> 00:47:25.190
than it should be, although I'm--

00:47:25.190 --> 00:47:28.010
&gt;&gt; Sy Damle: But Krauss
acknowledged that there could be--

00:47:28.010 --> 00:47:30.890
I mean it didn't find the license
in that case but it acknowledged

00:47:30.890 --> 00:47:32.540
that there could be licenses.

00:47:32.540 --> 00:47:33.840
&gt;&gt; Aaron Perzanowski:
Yeah that's right.

00:47:33.840 --> 00:47:35.690
Yeah, I think the conceptual
framework that courts used

00:47:35.690 --> 00:47:38.430 position:56%
to answer this question is confused.

00:47:38.430 --> 00:47:42.490
A couple of other points here.

00:47:42.490 --> 00:47:46.680
You know, one of the questions
that came up is, you know,

00:47:46.680 --> 00:47:53.050
what's the value of a license
that purports to deny a transfer

00:47:53.050 --> 00:47:57.650
of ownership to a consumer?

00:47:57.650 --> 00:47:59.610
And there's a lot of value there.

00:47:59.610 --> 00:48:01.600
It's value that I think
we should question

00:48:01.600 --> 00:48:05.220
from an overall social
utility standpoint, right?

00:48:05.220 --> 00:48:07.640
It's about restricting resale,

00:48:07.640 --> 00:48:11.740
it's about controlling
aftermarket products,

00:48:11.740 --> 00:48:16.010
it is about controlling
the market for services.

00:48:16.010 --> 00:48:18.600
It might be about price
discrimination

00:48:18.600 --> 00:48:22.130
and we can have a debate about the
merits of price discrimination.

00:48:22.130 --> 00:48:27.610
There are other means other
than denying consumers the right

00:48:27.610 --> 00:48:29.360
to own the things that
they purchased

00:48:29.360 --> 00:48:31.160
to achieve price discrimination.

00:48:31.160 --> 00:48:34.520 position:56%
I think it's worth pointing out that
the Supreme Court was really clear

00:48:34.520 --> 00:48:37.910
in Kirtsaeng that price
discrimination is not among the

00:48:37.910 --> 00:48:45.120 position:56%
rights that copyright holders get to
enjoy by virtue of their copyright.

00:48:45.120 --> 00:48:46.420
So if--

00:48:46.420 --> 00:48:47.720
&gt;&gt; Sy Damle: If you would
acknowledge that there are--

00:48:47.720 --> 00:48:49.360
I mean this is sort of like
basic economics, right?

00:48:49.360 --> 00:48:51.860
I mean there are consumer
benefits to allowing

00:48:51.860 --> 00:48:53.160
for price discrimination.

00:48:53.160 --> 00:48:55.330
&gt;&gt; Aaron Perzanowski:
There certainly can be,

00:48:55.330 --> 00:48:58.190
but I would not say that price
discrimination is necessarily

00:48:58.190 --> 00:49:01.890 position:56%
overall to the benefit of consumers.

00:49:01.890 --> 00:49:04.480
There are certain circumstances
where price discrimination it is

00:49:04.480 --> 00:49:07.860
in fact very useful for consumers.

00:49:07.860 --> 00:49:10.910
But denying consumers' ownership

00:49:10.910 --> 00:49:15.940
and imposing ongoing copyright
obligations is not the only way

00:49:15.940 --> 00:49:17.240
to price discriminate.

00:49:17.240 --> 00:49:18.590
There are lots of industries
that price discriminate

00:49:18.590 --> 00:49:21.150
that don't use copyright
law whatsoever.

00:49:21.150 --> 00:49:25.930
And, you know, I think we've
seen in the wake of Kirtsaeng

00:49:25.930 --> 00:49:29.080
that price discrimination
in the market

00:49:29.080 --> 00:49:32.040
for academic textbooks continues.

00:49:32.040 --> 00:49:34.950
There are other ways
of achieving that goal.

00:49:34.950 --> 00:49:40.370 position:56%
One way of achieving that goal is to
not sell products to people, right?

00:49:40.370 --> 00:49:43.910
Don't engage in transactions
that look like sales.

00:49:43.910 --> 00:49:45.610
Engage in transactions that look

00:49:45.610 --> 00:49:48.480
like subscriptions
that look like rentals.

00:49:48.480 --> 00:49:51.660
You know, my students have the
option to get their case books

00:49:51.660 --> 00:49:54.650
in law school on a
rental model, right,

00:49:54.650 --> 00:49:56.990 position:56%
or on an ongoing subscription model.

00:49:56.990 --> 00:50:00.110
That at least is an honest way
of engaging with consumers.

00:50:00.110 --> 00:50:04.110
You're not characterizing
in a transaction as a sale

00:50:04.110 --> 00:50:06.760
when in fact you don't
believe that it's a sale.

00:50:06.760 --> 00:50:09.980
You know, those kinds
of transactions carry

00:50:09.980 --> 00:50:11.900
with them expectations

00:50:11.900 --> 00:50:15.030
that consumers think they're
getting a certain set of rights

00:50:15.030 --> 00:50:17.070
when they buy a product, right?

00:50:17.070 --> 00:50:22.310
When you go and you buy that new
refrigerator, you think you own it.

00:50:22.310 --> 00:50:25.520
You don't think you're entering
into an ongoing relationship

00:50:25.520 --> 00:50:27.600
with the service provider, right?

00:50:27.600 --> 00:50:30.840
That's what you do with
your cable company.

00:50:30.840 --> 00:50:34.570
I won't say more about what people
think of their cable companies.

00:50:34.570 --> 00:50:39.300
You know, but when you buy a
refrigerator, you think you own it.

00:50:39.300 --> 00:50:41.450
You think you have a
certain set of rights.

00:50:41.450 --> 00:50:47.290
I just-- I have a study that
was just published last Friday

00:50:47.290 --> 00:50:51.040
that looks at this question in the
context of digital media that looks

00:50:51.040 --> 00:50:55.450
at the Buy Now button used
prominently by Amazon and Apple,

00:50:55.450 --> 00:50:59.190
and finds that consumers believe
they have the right to engage

00:50:59.190 --> 00:51:05.120
in a resale with digital media
that they buy now to lend

00:51:05.120 --> 00:51:09.160
that digital media to
others to give it away,

00:51:09.160 --> 00:51:11.260
to leave it in their will, right?

00:51:11.260 --> 00:51:16.140
So when you set up a transaction,
when you present it to consumers

00:51:16.140 --> 00:51:20.040
in the context of a sale,
they have expectations

00:51:20.040 --> 00:51:21.470
about what they're getting.

00:51:21.470 --> 00:51:23.810
And the fact that some
license agreement that no one

00:51:23.810 --> 00:51:27.470
in their right mind would invest
the time to read, you know,

00:51:27.470 --> 00:51:31.890
includes terms to the contrary
does not change those consumer

00:51:31.890 --> 00:51:34.200
expectations, right?

00:51:34.200 --> 00:51:40.330
So, this isn't to say that we can't
allow for flexible business models

00:51:40.330 --> 00:51:46.340
that give software companies
the kinds of protections

00:51:46.340 --> 00:51:47.640
that they think they need.

00:51:47.640 --> 00:51:48.940
You can look at what Adobe has done

00:51:48.940 --> 00:51:51.700
with its Creative Suite
over the last few years.

00:51:51.700 --> 00:51:53.000
You can't buy it anymore.

00:51:53.000 --> 00:51:55.960
You can pay Adobe $50 a month
for the rest of your life

00:51:55.960 --> 00:51:59.630
if you're creative professional
to use their software.

00:51:59.630 --> 00:52:00.970
And in a lot of ways, I think

00:52:00.970 --> 00:52:04.590
that was really smart
decision on their part, right?

00:52:04.590 --> 00:52:09.420
It avoids the problems
that they saw with resale.

00:52:09.420 --> 00:52:13.820
It allows them a, you know,
more predictable revenue stream.

00:52:13.820 --> 00:52:17.100
It allows them to deliver
product updates

00:52:17.100 --> 00:52:19.730
to consumers in a more
effective way.

00:52:19.730 --> 00:52:21.530
And it's a really honest
transaction.

00:52:21.530 --> 00:52:24.500
You know what you're
getting from the outset.

00:52:24.500 --> 00:52:28.150
&gt;&gt; Sy Damle: So is this the
problem that's going to diminish

00:52:28.150 --> 00:52:30.880
as we go forward, because
as we move, you know,

00:52:30.880 --> 00:52:36.030
more and more into kind of
cloud-based services the sort

00:52:36.030 --> 00:52:40.800
of problems that you've identified
are kind of problems of the moment.

00:52:40.800 --> 00:52:44.260 position:56%
But, you know, we have Office 365,
there's like all sorts of other ways

00:52:44.260 --> 00:52:46.510
in which where now
software is moving

00:52:46.510 --> 00:52:49.490
into like cloud-based
subscription models.

00:52:49.490 --> 00:52:50.790
&gt;&gt; Aaron Perzanowski:
So in some ways--

00:52:50.790 --> 00:52:52.830 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Sy Damle: And then the reason I'm
asking that is because, you know,

00:52:52.830 --> 00:52:56.810
if we're looking ahead, if we're
solving yesterday's problem,

00:52:56.810 --> 00:52:58.800
it doesn't make very much sense.

00:52:58.800 --> 00:53:00.100
&gt;&gt; Erik Bertin: I'm sorry.

00:53:00.100 --> 00:53:01.830
Can I just add one
point on top of that?

00:53:01.830 --> 00:53:06.420
I mean the Adobe example you
cite is a good one but sort

00:53:06.420 --> 00:53:10.380
of the logic behind your
argument is that the physicality

00:53:10.380 --> 00:53:11.720
of the Adobe product is gone.

00:53:11.720 --> 00:53:13.620
There is no longer a CD
that you're purchasing.

00:53:13.620 --> 00:53:15.470
It's-- You're just simply
downloading the product,

00:53:15.470 --> 00:53:18.110
as opposed to your
refrigerator which is physical

00:53:18.110 --> 00:53:19.410
in every sense the, the
word, it's going to be

00:53:19.410 --> 00:53:20.710
with you for a long time.

00:53:20.710 --> 00:53:22.010
So is there a distinction there?

00:53:22.010 --> 00:53:23.310
&gt;&gt; Aaron Perzanowski: Yeah.

00:53:23.310 --> 00:53:24.610
Well, I think in the Adobe example,
you're not buying anything, right?

00:53:24.610 --> 00:53:28.480
That transaction is absolutely on
the rental, lease, or lending side

00:53:28.480 --> 00:53:31.980
of this divide in Section 1063.

00:53:31.980 --> 00:53:33.540
So I don't think there's
any good argument

00:53:33.540 --> 00:53:35.150
that the consumer owns anything.

00:53:35.150 --> 00:53:39.250
You know, they're paying
for a service.

00:53:39.250 --> 00:53:42.210
In terms of whether this
is yesterday's problem

00:53:42.210 --> 00:53:45.410
or tomorrow's problem, in
some ways I think for markets

00:53:45.410 --> 00:53:50.470
for pure software products,
we are going to see a move

00:53:50.470 --> 00:53:55.400
in this direction towards
cloud-based services.

00:53:55.400 --> 00:53:58.690
The area where I think
we need to be focusing

00:53:58.690 --> 00:54:02.600
as I think we are here
today, is what happens

00:54:02.600 --> 00:54:06.170
when we see software
embedded in everyday products

00:54:06.170 --> 00:54:08.740
that consumers use everyday, right?

00:54:08.740 --> 00:54:14.430
There, there is necessarily a
kind of a physical embodiment

00:54:14.430 --> 00:54:18.080
of the work and of the product.

00:54:18.080 --> 00:54:20.750
And so, in those circumstances,

00:54:20.750 --> 00:54:25.720 position:56%
I don't think you can escape these
questions, right, because the nature

00:54:25.720 --> 00:54:30.230
of the product embeds
that kind of physicality.

00:54:30.230 --> 00:54:37.010
And unless we start to see-- which
I'm doubtful about, unless we start

00:54:37.010 --> 00:54:41.340
to see really explicit shift to now
you don't buy your home appliances,

00:54:41.340 --> 00:54:44.140
you lease your home
appliances, we're going to have

00:54:44.140 --> 00:54:47.270
to face this question of who
owns the software that makes

00:54:47.270 --> 00:54:48.570
that product work, right?

00:54:48.570 --> 00:54:52.980
The software is just as important
to the functioning of your car

00:54:52.980 --> 00:54:57.450
or your new smart refrigerator
or your smart TV as any

00:54:57.450 --> 00:54:58.900
of the physical component.

00:54:58.900 --> 00:55:06.060
So to tell consumers, sure, you own
the plastic and you own the chips

00:55:06.060 --> 00:55:07.780
and you own the display,

00:55:07.780 --> 00:55:09.690
but the thing that actually
makes the thing work,

00:55:09.690 --> 00:55:11.940
the thing that actually
makes the thing valuable,

00:55:11.940 --> 00:55:14.060
someone else controls that.

00:55:14.060 --> 00:55:17.090
That puts consumers in a really
precarious situation, right?

00:55:17.090 --> 00:55:20.230
Think about-- I missed the
beginning of the first panel,

00:55:20.230 --> 00:55:22.360
so I'm sure someone has
already mentioned revolve.

00:55:22.360 --> 00:55:25.390
But look at what happened
with that device.

00:55:25.390 --> 00:55:28.530
Consumers went out, they
bought this device for $300,

00:55:28.530 --> 00:55:30.440
this home automation hub.

00:55:30.440 --> 00:55:31.740
They thought they owned it.

00:55:31.740 --> 00:55:34.070
They thought they got to use it as
long as they wanted until one day,

00:55:34.070 --> 00:55:35.370
they got a message that said, "Oh,

00:55:35.370 --> 00:55:37.990
that thing you bought,
it's a brick," right?

00:55:37.990 --> 00:55:40.010
It's useless now.

00:55:40.010 --> 00:55:42.570
Because they don't own and
they don't control the software

00:55:42.570 --> 00:55:43.960
that makes it operate.

00:55:43.960 --> 00:55:46.560
That puts consumers in a
really precarious position.

00:55:46.560 --> 00:55:48.840
So, you know, I'm worried
about a future

00:55:48.840 --> 00:55:53.760
where consumers have this illusion
of ongoing personal property rights

00:55:53.760 --> 00:55:56.310
that they have enjoyed,
you know, for centuries.

