01:17:43.610 --> 01:17:46.770
in finding out about.

01:17:46.770 --> 01:17:48.350
&gt;&gt; Michelle Choe: Mr. Bergmayer.

01:17:48.350 --> 01:17:49.650
&gt;&gt; John Bergmayer: OK.

01:17:49.650 --> 01:17:50.950
You know, just for the record,

01:17:50.950 --> 01:17:53.330
open source software is not
dependent of licensing copies.

01:17:53.330 --> 01:17:55.960
It's dependent on licensing
intellectual property rights,

01:17:55.960 --> 01:17:59.240
that the licensee otherwise would
not have in placing conditions

01:17:59.240 --> 01:18:01.770
on those rights, which
is totally legit.

01:18:01.770 --> 01:18:04.540
So, for example, the GPL grants
to the licensee the right

01:18:04.540 --> 01:18:07.340
to make reproductions or the
right to make derivative works.

01:18:07.340 --> 01:18:09.270
Licensees don't otherwise
have those rights.

01:18:09.270 --> 01:18:11.260
So putting conditions
on those is fine.

01:18:11.260 --> 01:18:12.980
And I don't have an
objection to that.

01:18:12.980 --> 01:18:14.940
Those licenses do not
depend on saying

01:18:14.940 --> 01:18:19.060
that the ultimate user does not own
a copy of the software in question.

01:18:19.060 --> 01:18:20.830
I think that is very
important distinction.

01:18:20.830 --> 01:18:24.090
Second, I think, you know,
let's say for the sake

01:18:24.090 --> 01:18:25.990
of argument that I own this iPhone.

01:18:25.990 --> 01:18:29.300
When I install an app on it, I
think I own a copy of that app.

01:18:29.300 --> 01:18:32.620
A copy is defined is the
statute as a material thing,

01:18:32.620 --> 01:18:35.070
the only material thing
I see is the iPhone,

01:18:35.070 --> 01:18:37.310
therefore I necessarily own a copy.

01:18:37.310 --> 01:18:39.860
I don't think there are
negative consequences of that

01:18:39.860 --> 01:18:41.460
for the software developer.

01:18:41.460 --> 01:18:42.760
What does it mean?

01:18:42.760 --> 01:18:45.270
It means I can operate the software
without needing a specific license

01:18:45.270 --> 01:18:49.200
by virtue of the essential step
test, the essential step doctrine

01:18:49.200 --> 01:18:52.620
which says that I'm entitled to
make RAM copies that are necessary

01:18:52.620 --> 01:18:54.720
to use physical items that I own.

01:18:54.720 --> 01:18:56.700
I don't think that's bad
for software developers.

01:18:56.700 --> 01:18:58.790
And it might mean that
first-sale applies.

01:18:58.790 --> 01:19:02.080
But as a practical matter in
today's technological environment,

01:19:02.080 --> 01:19:03.380
what I'm going to do?

01:19:03.380 --> 01:19:06.190
Sell my entire phone
including my iTunes account?

01:19:06.190 --> 01:19:08.540
That's really not going to happen.

01:19:08.540 --> 01:19:10.100
I think it could happen if I were

01:19:10.100 --> 01:19:13.780
to sell my iPhone including
my iTunes Store account

01:19:13.780 --> 01:19:15.080
that is tied to.

01:19:15.080 --> 01:19:16.930
I think I should be allowed
to do that and I think that's

01:19:16.930 --> 01:19:18.580
where first-sale kicks in.

01:19:18.580 --> 01:19:21.370
But as a practical matter, you
know, first-sale doesn't entitle me

01:19:21.370 --> 01:19:24.330
to make arbitrary numbers of
new copies and resell them.

01:19:24.330 --> 01:19:27.310
It doesn't entitle me to engage
in piracy in any respect.

01:19:27.310 --> 01:19:31.600
In fact, the main thing that saying
that I own a copy of software

01:19:31.600 --> 01:19:33.100
that I bought even in the case

01:19:33.100 --> 01:19:37.600 position:56%
of an Adobe Creative Cloud situation
is simple to say that simply

01:19:37.600 --> 01:19:41.500
by virtue of owning it, I don't
need a license just to use it.

01:19:41.500 --> 01:19:42.860
It doesn't grant any new rights.

01:19:42.860 --> 01:19:44.460
It doesn't necessarily
even entitle me

01:19:44.460 --> 01:19:46.410
to software updates in the future.

01:19:46.410 --> 01:19:50.310
And I don't think that is
bad for a software developer,

01:19:50.310 --> 01:19:52.810
and I have a hard time seeing
why there is such resistance

01:19:52.810 --> 01:19:56.870
to this concept which is grounded
in a claim text of the statute

01:19:56.870 --> 01:19:59.550
that one, copies are
material items, and two,

01:19:59.550 --> 01:20:02.130
if I own the material
item I own the copy.

01:20:02.130 --> 01:20:04.130
I don't-- I have very difficulty--

01:20:04.130 --> 01:20:08.410
a very much difficulty in seeing
the resistance to that except

01:20:08.410 --> 01:20:12.260
for the fact that by saying
that you don't own the copy,

01:20:12.260 --> 01:20:15.420
that brings up the RAM copy's
doctrine and it allows you

01:20:15.420 --> 01:20:19.250 position:56%
to put all kinds of restrictions and
sort of gin up copyright violations

01:20:19.250 --> 01:20:22.530
for what otherwise be a
routine contract violation.

01:20:22.530 --> 01:20:25.740
So, those are my two final points.

01:20:25.740 --> 01:20:27.380
&gt;&gt; Erik Bertin: So
